The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Kanpur, Sept. 26 (PTI): A teenaged girl allegedly hanged herself on Friday after her parents asked her to give up studies as they could not afford her school fees.           
	Rakhi Yadav, 16, of Class XI had received a notice from her school for failing to pay two months fees. When she reminded her father, a milkman, about it, he allegedly asked her to discontinue studies.                  
	 Raipur (PTI): The death toll from Wednesdays chimney collapse at the Balco plant in Chhattisgarhs Korba district has risen to 40. Korba collector Ashok Agrawal said on Saturday that the bodies of 40 labourers had been dug out and the operation to clear the debris was expected to continue till Sunday.                   
	 Pune (PTI): The Pune municipal corporation has raised the fine amount for spitting in public places from Rs 25 to Rs 1,000. Municipal commissioner Mahesh Zagde said the step was taken in view of the H1N1 pandemic that has claimed 61 lives in the city so far.                  
	 Islamabad (PTI): A Pakistan court on Saturday put off till October 3 the trial of seven suspects in the Mumbai attack case, including Lashkar-e-Toiba top gun Zakiur Rehman Lakhvi, as the judge was on leave. The foreign ministers of India and Pakistan will meet in New York on Sunday and discuss the progress Pakistan has made in the 26/11 probe.                  
	 Jammu (PTI): A Jammu court has sentenced a Pakistani militant to life imprisonment for planting a bomb in a van that killed seven people in 1994. Sanaullah was caught in 1995 while crossing over to India.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The CBI is still investigating Vijai Lakshmi Sharma, the first woman chief of the revenue intelligence department, in a corruption case dating back to 2001, sources in the agency have said. The residence of Sharma, then the customs commissioner, Delhi, had been searched by the CBI in 2001 in connection with a case of alleged duty evasion by Essar Oil Limited.                                                                                                                           
